    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-01-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-01-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="692"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d692">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.124a/123</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Ambassador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lindsay</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-01-23">January 23,
                            1931</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 16</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honour to inform you that, on being
                    apprised of the circumstances in which the United States Government had been
                    obliged to conclude that the further presence of Surgeon Howard F. Smith in
                    Liberia as Chief Medical Adviser could not be justified and to direct him to
                    return to the United States,<note n="23" xml:id="d692fn23">See memorandum of
                        December 12, 1930, to the British Embassy, <ref target="frus1930v03#pg_441">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1930, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 441</ref>.</note> His Majesty’s
                    Government instructed His Majesty’s Chargé d’Affaires at Monrovia to inform the
                    Liberian Government that they had learnt with profound displeasure of the
                    failure of the Liberian Government to take advantage of Dr. Smith’s advice and
                    of the small measure of support which that Government had accorded to him.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">R. C. Lindsay</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
